    {
        "content": "<p>For thread, even in C, creating a thread is not encouraged as kernel threads are important resources and justification is needed to use a kernel thread. The general advice is to use something like <code>workqueue</code>. So please look into using workqueue for your usage.</p>\n<p>But I did have  a <a href=\"https://github.com/Rust-for-Linux/linux/pull/109\">PR</a> back in the old time. And just rebase on the latest <code>rust-next</code>: <a href=\"https://github.com/fbq/linux/tree/dev/rust/thread\">https://github.com/fbq/linux/tree/dev/rust/thread</a></p>\n<p>For ftrace, it's currently not supported, but it shouldn't be that hard (famous last words), IIUC, you will just need to make sure Rust functions work with <code>ftrace_modify_all_code()</code> (maybe additional calling convention need to be handled as well?)</p>",
        "id": 479153983,
        "sender_full_name": "Boqun Feng",
        "timestamp": 1730053249
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://rust.docs.kernel.org/kernel/workqueue/index.html\">https://rust.docs.kernel.org/kernel/workqueue/index.html</a></p>\n<p>Nice, i found this doc. Thanks.. </p>\n<p>There are any alternative to tracing functions similar ftrace, for Rust modules?</p>",
        "id": 479158695,
        "sender_full_name": "Filipe Xavier",
        "timestamp": 1730057453
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Not yet. ftrace would be nice though. <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"519727\">@Alice Ryhl</span> has submitted patches for tracepoints.</p>",
